Project and Cluster Quotas
Goal
Allow developers from multiple teams to safely create workloads in the cluster without exhausting cluster resources.
Administrators achieve this by configuring:
•	Resource Quotas
•	Cluster Resource Quotas
•	Limit Ranges
•	Project Templates
•	Self-provisioner roles
________________________________________
1. Why Resource Control is Needed
In a Kubernetes / OpenShift cluster:
•	Multiple users deploy applications.
•	Applications consume CPU, memory, storage, and pods.
•	Cluster resources are limited.
If one user deploys many workloads:
•	CPU or memory may be exhausted.
•	Other applications may fail.
•	Autoscaling clusters may create unexpected costs.
To solve this, Kubernetes provides:
1️⃣ Resource Requests
Minimum resources required for a container.
Example:
•	CPU needed to run
•	Memory needed to start
If cluster doesn’t have these resources → pod will not be scheduled.
Example:
resources:
  requests:
    cpu: 500m
    memory: 256Mi
Meaning:
Resource	Meaning
500m CPU	0.5 CPU core required
256Mi	Minimum memory needed
________________________________________
2️⃣ Resource Limits
Maximum resources a container can consume.
Example:
resources:
  limits:
    cpu: 1
    memory: 512Mi
Meaning:
Resource	Meaning
1 CPU	Container cannot exceed 1 CPU
512Mi	Memory usage cannot exceed 512MB
If container exceeds memory → pod may be killed.
________________________________________
2. Resource Quotas
A ResourceQuota restricts how many resources a namespace (project) can consume.
Important point:
⚠️ ResourceQuota works per namespace, not per user.
Example:
Namespace: project-dev
All workloads inside this namespace share the quota.
________________________________________
ResourceQuota YAML Example
apiVersion: v1
kind: ResourceQuota
metadata:
  name: memory
  namespace: example
spec:
  hard:
    limits.memory: 4Gi
    requests.memory: 2Gi
Explanation:
Field	Meaning
limits.memory	Max memory containers can use
requests.memory	Max memory containers can reserve
hard	Maximum allowed values
Meaning:
Total memory used by pods in namespace cannot exceed 4GB.
________________________________________
3. Types of Resource Quotas
1️⃣ Compute Resource Quotas
Control CPU and memory usage.
Examples:
Resource	Meaning
limits.cpu	Max CPU usage
limits.memory	Max memory usage
requests.cpu	Max CPU reservation
requests.memory	Max memory reservation
Example scenario:
Namespace limit = 4 CPU
Pods inside namespace:
Pod	CPU
Pod1	1
Pod2	1
Pod3	2
Total = 4 CPU
Another pod requesting CPU → ❌ rejected
________________________________________
2️⃣ Object Count Quotas
Limits number of Kubernetes objects.
Examples:
Object	Syntax
Pods	count/pods
Deployments	count/deployments.apps
Services	count/services
Example:
Limit pods to 1.
Command:
oc create quota example --hard=count/pods=1
Meaning:
Namespace can only run 1 pod.
________________________________________
4. Creating Resource Quotas
Using CLI
Command:
oc create resourcequota <name> --hard=<resource>=<value>
Example:
oc create quota example --hard=count/pods=1
Short form:
quota = resourcequota
Output:
resourcequota/example created
________________________________________
5. Viewing Resource Quotas
List quotas
oc get quota
Example output:
NAME      REQUEST        LIMIT
example   count/pods:1/1
Meaning:
Value	Meaning
1/1	1 pod used out of 1 allowed
________________________________________
View detailed quota
oc describe quota example
or
oc get quota example -o yaml
Example output:
status:
  hard:
    count/pods: "1"
  used:
    count/pods: "0"
Meaning:
Field	Meaning
hard	maximum allowed
used	currently used
________________________________________
6. Troubleshooting Resource Quotas
Example mistake:
count/deployment=1
Wrong syntax.
Correct syntax:
count/deployments.apps
Why?
Because deployments belong to apps API group.
________________________________________
Error Example
oc create deployment --image=nginx hello
Error:
exceeded quota
Meaning:
Quota limit reached.
________________________________________
Indirect failures
Sometimes:
Deployment created successfully but pods fail.
Check events:
oc get events
Example message:
FailedCreate: exceeded quota
Meaning:
Pod creation blocked by quota.
________________________________________
7. Cluster Resource Quotas
Problem:
ResourceQuota only works per namespace.
But sometimes:
One team has multiple namespaces.
Example:
Team Dev:
dev-project1
dev-project2
dev-project3
Admin wants to limit total CPU usage of the entire team.
Solution:
ClusterResourceQuota
Works across multiple namespaces.
________________________________________
Example YAML
apiVersion: quota.openshift.io/v1
kind: ClusterResourceQuota
metadata:
  name: example
spec:
  quota:
    hard:
      requests.cpu: "10"
  selector:
    labels:
      matchLabels:
        group: dev
Meaning:
All namespaces with label:
group=dev
share 10 CPU total.
________________________________________
8. Creating Cluster Resource Quota
Command:
oc create clusterresourcequota example \
--project-label-selector=group=dev \
--hard=requests.cpu=10
Explanation:
Part	Meaning
clusterresourcequota	resource type
project-label-selector	select namespaces
requests.cpu=10	CPU limit
________________________________________
9. Checking Cluster Resource Quotas
Command:
oc describe AppliedClusterResourceQuota -n <namespace>
Example:
Resource        Used    Hard
requests.cpu    2250m   10
Meaning:
Value	Meaning
Used	current CPU
Hard	maximum allowed
